Looking for numbers such that

$$
(digit sum)^n = a \; .
$$

Note that
$$
digit sum = a mod 9
$$
so
$$
(digit sum)^n = a^n = a mod 9
$$
This forces $a^n = a$.

This gives some cutdown.

$a^2 = a \mod 9$ gives $a=0,1$.
$a^3 = a \mod 9$ gives $a=0,1,-1$.
$a^4 = a \mod 9$ gives $a=0,1,4,7$.
$a^5 = a \mod 9$ gives $a=0,1,-1$.

## Idea

Brute force over powers.
Look at $a^n$ and see if digit sum equals $a$.
